<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features to Evaluate in Med Spa Software</h2>

Not all features matter equally. Here's what separates adequate platforms from exceptional ones, based on what breaks first when you scale.

<h3>Medical Charting and Consent Management</h3>

This is non-negotiable, and it's where most generic booking platforms fail completely. Look for:

- Treatment-specific SOAP note templates that actually match your protocols
- Injection mapping tools with dose tracking per anatomical zone
- Photo documentation with automatic patient consent workflows
- E-signature capture that holds up legally in your state
- Provider-specific credential tracking with expiration alerts

The best platforms pre-populate treatment notes based on the service booked, cutting documentation time by 40-60% compared to free-form entry. Pabau excels here with customizable medical forms that sync across the patient journey.

<h3>Inventory Management for Injectables</h3>

Injectable inventory is where med spas hemorrhage profit without realizing it. A single vial of Sculptra costs $400+ wholesale. If your system can't track:

- Units used per treatment with provider attribution
- Lot numbers for recall compliance
- Waste and breakage
- Par levels and automated reorder alerts

...you're flying blind on your highest-margin services. We've audited practices losing $30,000+ annually to injectable shrinkage that proper inventory tracking would catch.

<h3>Membership and Package Management</h3>

Med spa revenue increasingly depends on recurring membership revenue. Your platform must handle:

- Flexible membership tiers with different included services
- Automatic monthly billing with failed payment recovery
- Package tracking showing remaining treatments
- Easy redemption workflows that don't slow down checkout

<h3>Marketing Automation and Recall</h3>

Patient lifetime value in med spa depends on rebooking. Botox patients need reminders at 3-4 months. Laser patients need series completion follow-up. Your platform should automate:

- Treatment-specific recall campaigns
- Birthday and anniversary offers
- Abandoned cart recovery for online bookings
- Review generation sequences

For deeper strategy on retention, see our guide on [customer retention systems for service businesses](/guides/customer-retention-strategies).

<h3>Reporting and Analytics</h3>

You can't optimize what you can't measure. Essential reports include:

- Revenue by provider, treatment type, and location
- Utilization rates (are your treatment rooms sitting empty?)
- Retail vs. service revenue mix
- Patient acquisition cost by marketing channel
- Membership churn and lifetime value

